            <p>The following example, from the prelude to Act I of Richard Wagner's opera <booktitle>Tristan und Isolde</booktitle>, is arguably one of the most famous deceptive cadences in the history of music.</p>
            <figure>
                <caption>Wagner, <booktitle>Tristan und Isolde</booktitle>, Prelude to Act I</caption>
                <idx><h>Wagner, Richard</h><h>Tristan und Isolde, Prelude to Act I</h></idx>
                <sbsgroup>
                    <sidebyside>
                        <image source="images/unit2/cadences-deceptive-cad-tristan">
                            <description>Deceptive cadence at bar 17 of prelude to Act One of Tristan und Isolde by Richard Wagner</description>
                        </image>
                    </sidebyside>
                    <sidebyside margins="37%">
                        <video youtube="cq4uPQUGrgM" start="113" end="128" play-at="select" preview="generic"/>
                    </sidebyside>
                </sbsgroup>
            </figure>
            <p>A deceptive cadence means <chord root="V"/> did not go to <chord root="I"/>. This means that <q><chord root="V"/> to not<ndash/><chord root="I"/></q> is technically a more correct description for a deceptive cadence than <chord root="V"/><ndash/><chord root="vi"/>, which is the most common realization of <q><chord root="V"/> to not<ndash/><chord root="I"/>.</q></p>
            <p>In the example below, <chord root="V"/> goes to <chord root="IV" bass="3rd"/>.</p>
